    "prompt_variants": [
      {
        "prompt_id": "simple",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_SIMPLE",
        "query_text": "Recommend a cryptographic architecture for this secure messaging app. Briefly explain what should be used and why."
      },
      {
        "prompt_id": "structured",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_STRUCTURED",
        "query_text": "You are designing the end-to-end cryptographic architecture for a multi-device messaging system.\n\nRead the project brief and produce a structured design note.\n\nYour answer must use the following headings:\n1. Threat Model Assumptions\n2. Session Establishment\n3. Message and Attachment Encryption\n4. Identity Authentication\n5. Ongoing Key Update / Ratcheting\n6. Residual Risks\n\nRequirements:\n- Assume attackers may record encrypted traffic today and that some message confidentiality must hold for 10 to 15 years.\n- Name concrete algorithms or standards for each role.\n- Do not use generic placeholders like 'public-key encryption' or 'symmetric encryption'.\n- Keep the roles separate instead of describing one primitive as the whole solution."
      },
      {
        "prompt_id": "pqc_simple",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_PQC_SIMPLE",
        "query_text": "Recommend a cryptographic architecture for this secure messaging app. Briefly explain what should be used and why. Consider post-quantum risks where relevant."
      },
      {
        "prompt_id": "pqc_structured",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_PQC_STRUCTURED",
        "query_text": "You are designing the end-to-end cryptographic architecture for a multi-device messaging system.\n\nRead the project brief and produce a structured design note.\n\nYour answer must use the following headings:\n1. Threat Model Assumptions\n2. Session Establishment\n3. Message and Attachment Encryption\n4. Identity Authentication\n5. Ongoing Key Update / Ratcheting\n6. Residual Risks\n\nRequirements:\n- Assume attackers may record encrypted traffic today and that some message confidentiality must hold for 10 to 15 years.\n- Name concrete algorithms or standards for each role.\n- Do not use generic placeholders like 'public-key encryption' or 'symmetric encryption'.\n- Keep the roles separate instead of describing one primitive as the whole solution.\n- Briefly mention any post-quantum cryptography considerations or future PQC requirements relevant to long-term message confidentiality."
      },
      {
        "prompt_id": "nist_pqc_simple",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_NIST_PQC_SIMPLE",
        "query_text": "Recommend a cryptographic architecture for this secure messaging app. Briefly explain what should be used and why. Prefer NIST-approved post-quantum approaches where relevant."
      },
      {
        "prompt_id": "nist_pqc_structured",
        "query_name": "MESSAGING_ROLE_MAP_NIST_PQC_STRUCTURED",
        "query_text": "You are designing the end-to-end cryptographic architecture for a multi-device messaging system.\n\nRead the project brief and produce a structured design note.\n\nYour answer must use the following headings:\n1. Threat Model Assumptions\n2. Session Establishment\n3. Message and Attachment Encryption\n4. Identity Authentication\n5. Ongoing Key Update / Ratcheting\n6. Residual Risks\n\nRequirements:\n- Assume attackers may record encrypted traffic today and that some message confidentiality must hold for 10 to 15 years.\n- Name concrete algorithms or standards for each role.\n- Do not use generic placeholders like 'public-key encryption' or 'symmetric encryption'.\n- Keep the roles separate instead of describing one primitive as the whole solution.\n- Briefly mention any relevant NIST post-quantum cryptography guidance or migration direction where it affects long-term confidentiality, but do not let that replace the main role-specific architecture."
      }
    ],
